  "text": "The employed PL is fabricated using 10 single mode fibers with a core diameter of 13 µm, and are placed inside a low refractive index glass capillary. The fibers are accurately positioned to match the modal symmetry and prevent high losses [CITATION_1] . To achieve the geometry required to launch the 10 modes, the 3 inner SMFs (86 µm cladding diameter) are surrounded by 7 larger SMFs (125 µm cladding diameter), as illustrated on the left hand side of Fig. 2 [CITATION_2] . The flourine-doped silica capillary is then adiabatically tapered down from 900 μm to 57 μm within a transition length of 5.75 cm. The tapered facet of the PL is shown in Fig. 2 on the right inset image, and has an inner diameter of 28 μm, which matches to the 6-LP fiber dimensions and mode-fields as described in section 2. By consecutively addressing the individual ports and observing the PL output with an infrared camera (Xenics, XEVA-1.7-320), characterization of the near field intensity profiles is performed. As shown in Fig. 3 , notice that due to the non mode selectivity of the PLs, no discernable mode fields are visible for the near field mode profiles taken at 1550 nm, using a 50 nm bandwidth light source. With a DFB laser at 1540 nm and an integrating sphere detector, the excess losses of the ports have been measured. In addition, to fully capture the power of all modes and test port-by-port coupling losses, a graded index multimode fiber with core diameter 50 µm was butt-coupled to the PL for measurement. In both measurements, the power launched into the lantern is 0 dBm. The loss measurement results are depicted in Fig. 4 . From the excess losses, the MDL of the photonic lantern is estimated to be approximately 2 dB. The loss difference between the ports is partially attributed to alignment and connector losses. ",
